\par }\pard \qj \fi540\li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs24 
\par EM:\tab Edith Millman interviewing Mr. Daniel Goldsmith. Today is February 6, 1995. Mr. Goldsmith, could you tell me when and where you were born, and a little bit about your childhood and about your family?
\par DG:\tab OK I was born in Antwerp on December 11, 1931 to my parents who were originally from Poland. My father was Chaim Goldschmidt. He was from Rymanov, Poland. And my mother was Ruchel Goldschmidt, originally, her maiden name was M\'fc
nzer, and she was from Przemyszlany, Poland. They both met in Antwerp and got married and that\rquote s where they lived.
\par EM:\tab Could you tell me when they migrated to Antwerp?
\par DG:\tab My mother migrated to Antwerp in 1930, my f
ather migrated to Antwerp in 1928. My father had his own business. My father was a plumber, and he had his own business. He lived all the years that--of my childhood, we lived on one street in three different houses but on the same street, which was Korte
 Kiebit Straat [see pgs. 7&8] in Antwerp. That was in the Jewish section of Antwerp.
\par EM:\tab Was your father and mother religious?
\par DG:\tab Yes. My father and my mother were both Orthodox, modern Orthodox. My father didn\rquote t have the beard, but he was }{\i\fs24 Shomer Shabbes}{\fs24 . And my parents kept a kosher home, as well as they sent me to a }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 
. Because I went to a }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24  by the name of }{\i\fs24 Tachkemoni}{\fs24 , which I believe is still in existence today.
\par EM:\tab Was this in addition to your regular school?
\par DG:\tab No. No, I had both my secular and my religious education at the same school. It was an all day }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 .
\par EM:\tab Oh. Do you know if your parents had to pay for you to go to the }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 ?
\par DG:\tab Yes, they paid. My parents I would say basically were middle class people, so they had to pay for that, yes.
\par EM:\tab Did you have any siblings?
\par DG:\tab Yes, in December, 1939, the 26th of December, 1939, my sister was born. Actually, in between my sister and I my mother had a miscarriage. But my sister was born at that particular tim
e. So when the war started, it had already started, you know when she was born, because we look at the war having started in September, 1939.
\par EM:\tab Tell me, did your parents have contact with their family, if any, in Poland?
\par DG:\tab Yes. As a matter of fact, when I was small, my mother made a trip back to Poland to visit both my father\rquote 
s family and her own family. And I, as a matter of fact, I have some pictures, you know, that show me being in Poland. And they were constantly in touch with them.
\par EM:\tab Were any other members of your parents in Antwerp?
\par DG:\tab No. My mother and my father were alone in Antwerp. My father\rquote s family--most of my father\rquote s family was here in the United States. He had one sister--my father was one of nine children--so my father, one of his sist
ers, and his younger brother were the only ones that were left. And his younger brother had just also gone to the United States. So there were just my father and his sister that were left. The sister was left in Poland.
\par EM:\tab OK Could you tell me a little bit about antisemitism in Belgium, if any, as you were growing up?
\par DG:\tab I have to say that having gone to a }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 , and having lived in a Jewish area, OK, for the few--in my younger years--remember I was only nine years old--you know, when my father got take
n, or actually eight years old when the war started. I encountered very little antisemitism. Even though the street that we lived on was a half Jewish and a half non-Jewish, the people were basically nice to us, so that I did not have any problems. And of
 course, all my friends were, most of my friends I should say, you know, were Jewish.
\par EM:\tab Were Jewish, oh.
\par DG:\tab So I didn\rquote t encounter as a little boy.
\par EM:\tab So you didn\rquote t have much contact with non-Jewish...
\par DG:\tab Right.
\par EM:\tab ...frie-, people.
\par DG:\tab Right.
\par EM:\tab How about your parents? Do you think that they had much contact with non-Jews?
\par DG:\tab Yes, they did. They--my father being a plumber, OK, did work in a lot of the non-Jewish houses. My mother was very friendly with the non-Jewish people, you know, on our street. So they did have quite a bit of contact with them.
\par EM:\tab OK Do you happen to know if your parents were Zionists?
\par DG:\tab Yes. My parents were very strong Zionists. Matter of fact that\rquote s why, that\rquote s where I got my feeling for Zionism, you know, from them.
\par EM:\tab From there.
\par DG:\tab Yes.
\par EM:\tab Were there any Zionist organization that would take children as young as you, you know, to group meetings or so?
\par DG:\tab No, I was actually--we talked about that, you know, but I really was too young, you know, to go to attend any of those meetings.
\par EM:\tab OK What was the language of instruction in the }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 ?
\par DG:\tab The language of instruction in the }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24  was Flemish for the secular course and Yiddish for the Jewish instructions.
\par EM:\tab So there was secular instruction...
\par DG:\tab Yes.
\par EM:\tab ...at the same time.
\par DG:\tab At the same time, yes. Of course we learned Hebrew in the }{\i\fs24 yeshiva}{\fs24 .
\par EM:\tab Yeah. How--do you know how old you were when you started school?
\par DG:\tab Six.
\par EM:\tab You were six. What are your earliest memories of the war?
\par DG:\tab The earliest memories of the war actually were the discussions that my father and mother had, because living in Antwerp\emdash 
Antwerp at that particular time was a very big port of exit, and many, many people that my mother and my father knew from home, meaning from Poland, came through Antwerp to leave, basically, for the United States.
\par EM:\tab Do you know if your father tried to get an exit visa for...
\par DG:\tab Yes, yes, my father, as a matter of fact, tried very, very hard, you know, to get his family that was over here, you know, to send
 him an exit visa. And the family apparently did not take it as serious as my father took it, OK? Because they said, you know, \'93Why do you want to come over here? You know, you have a successful business over there.\'94
 Of course, you know, in retrospect you 
can also say that nobody knew what was going to happen of course, you know. It was just another war so to speak at that particular time. Although my parents sensed that it was much more than that because of the stories, you know, that people would tell, y
ou know, coming through, of what was happening in Germany and what was happening in Poland.
\par EM:\tab Right. What happened when the Germans invaded Belgium?
\par DG:\tab When the Germans invaded Belgium, we fled, like most of the Belgians actually did. We fled south. We went towards Ostend, you know, which is the seashore, you know, of Belgium, and then south towards France.
\par EM:\tab Right.
\par DG:\tab But the war in Belgium lasted a very short time. It was only two weeks. And so we were in Calais, which is in France, near the Belgian 
border, when the Germans caught up with us. And when that happened, there was nothing else that we could do except go back to Antwerp. And the ironic part of the whole thing is that it was at that particular time, just before the Germans invaded Belgium, 
that finally my father received the papers to go to the United States. By that time it was too late already, because the last ship had left and he couldn\rquote t leave anymore.
\par EM:\tab So he did get the papers...
\par DG:\tab Eventually.
\par EM:\tab But it, eventually.
\par DG:\tab It was too late.
\par EM:\tab When you came back to Amsterdam, did you go ba-...
\par DG:\tab Antwerp.
\par EM:\tab To Antwerp, I\rquote m sorry, did you go back to your own apartment, to your own house?
\par DG:\tab Yes. Yes, we went back to the house, because that was like in 1940. And actually life basica
lly went back to normal when we got back, meaning my father went back to work and I went back to school and everything was OK, you know, for a few months. And then after that little by little the sanctions started. You know we had heard...
\par EM:\tab The what?
\par DG:\tab Sanctions.
\par EM:\tab Sanctions against the...
\par DG:\tab Against the Jews. In other words we had curfews...
\par EM:\tab This, the curfew was different for you than for the Belgians? Or was there no cur-...
\par DG:\tab It was only for the Jews.
\par EM:\tab There was no curfew...
\par DG:\tab For the Belgians.
\par EM:\tab ...for the...
\par DG:\tab Yes, it was only for the Jews. Then they started closing down the schools. Teachers couldn\rquote t teach. Doctors, you know, couldn\rquote t practice anymore. My father couldn\rquote t do any work anymore. We had to wear the yellow star.
\par EM:\tab You had the yellow star, right?
\par DG:\tab Yes.
\par EM:\tab It was on the chest and on the...
\par DG:\tab It was on the chest on the jacket, yes.
\par EM:\tab Jacket. On the jacket.
\par DG:\tab Yeah, the yellow st-, we had to wear the yellow star. We couldn\rquote t go to the theater anymore, you
 know. All the civil rights were taken away, you know, little by little. And this went on until August, 1942 when my father received a notice to report to the train station for--I mean to go to a labor camp.
\par EM:\tab Was this the first time that you or your parents heard about labor camps or about people being taken to labor camps?
\par DG:\tab It, it--yes. This was not the first time in other words that my parents had heard, I mean, that there were labor camps. But this was the first time, I mean, that you know, he hear
d, you know, that they were going to take Jews away, you know, to labor camps in northern France.
\par EM:\tab In northern France.
\par DG:\tab Yes. In other words he knew he was going to France.
\par EM:\tab Oh, he knew that he was going to, he had to go to France.
\par DG:\tab To France. My father and my mother...
\par EM:\tab Were there any people, Jewish people, shipped out from Antwerp at that time, I mean to, young people?
\par DG:\tab Oh yes. Oh yes. They had thousands of them that were shipped out. There were, if I\rquote m not mistaken, a couple of transports.
\par EM:\tab That were going where?
\par DG:\tab That were going to, supposedly, to France.
\par EM:\tab Oh. Were these mostly young people? Were they men and women or just, do you know?
\par DG:\tab Men.
\par EM:\tab Only men.
\par DG:\tab Men. I don\rquote t know about how young they were, but that they were men.
\par EM:\tab Men, men.
\par DG:\tab My mother and my father had discussed, you know, because at that particular time, you know, a lot of people were starting to think about hiding, leaving the country by any which way, you know, and my father and my mother talked about i
t saying, well, he was in very good health. My father was, I\rquote m trying to remember he was like 40 years old, 42 years old. He was in good health. He said: \'93You know, the war has already been on for over two years, you know.\'94 He says, \'93
How much longer can it last, you know?\'94 He says, \'93I--you know, I think I\rquote ll go, you know, and I\rquote ll be back shortly. It\rquote s not gonna last very long.\'94
 That, I have to say that at that particular time, we had not heard about concentration camps.
\par EM:\tab And that was in 1942 or \lquote 43?
\par DG:\tab Two. We had not heard about concentration camps. We had heard about labor camps but not the concentration camps. That\rquote s the reason, you know, why my father actually decided to go. We went to the train station...
\par EM:\tab Do you remember what month  it was?
\par DG:\tab August.
\par EM:\tab It was in August.
\par DG:\tab August, 1942. August-Sept-...
\par EM:\tab Right after, yeah.
\par DG:\tab August-September, 1942.
\par EM:\tab Yeah, OK OK
\par DG:\tab We went to the train station. The--this is the time that I really remember quite vividly. [pause; tape off then on]
\par EM:\tab We have to interrupt for a while. Mr. Goldsmith is overcome by emotion. [tape off then on]
\par DG:\tab We went to this train station. My mother, my father, and my little sister and I. The train station in Antwerp is a huge, I mean huge, train station, a covered tr
ain station. And there were thousands and thousands of people, same as us, you know, saying good-bye. And my father said to me, he says, \'93You\rquote re now the man in the house.\'94 [weeping; tape off then on] Anyway, he said, \'93You\rquote 
re the man of the house now.\'94 And he says, \'93You\rquote ll have to take care of your mother and your sister until I come back.\'94
 And I told him I would. And that was the last time I saw my father. We heard from him a little bit later on. We received a post card which said that he was in France near Boulogne and that he was OK
\par }\pard \qj \fi540\li0\ri0\sl289\slmult0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs24 EM:\tab And that\rquote s all it said, that card?
\par DG:\tab That\rquote s all it said. I\rquote ll show you the card. And we went back to the house. We tried to live the normal life as possible, which was difficult, because, you\rquote ve got to remember my sister 
was a year-and-a-half old. And we were not used to all these restrictions, you know, which had been imposed.
\par EM:\tab How about financially since your father couldn\rquote t work much the previous year? Were you OK financially at that time?
\par DG:\tab Well, my mother was strapped financially, because--but we did have some money. And what she wound up doing is as she needed some money she would sell some of my father\rquote 
s tools, things like that, things that were precious. She had some sort of a foresight, I don\rquote t know, it\rquote s like
 a sixth sense. She figured, you know, things were gonna go wrong. And so she went across the street. We had this non-Jewish family that lived and had a grocery store. And she gave them our pictures. She asked them to hold onto our pictures. And she went 
to a couple of other neighbors and gave them our silverware to hold onto that, and gave to some other neighbors dishes, and to some other neighbors some of my father\rquote 
s tools so that they would be saved. Not everybody would have everything at the same time. And when my father would come back, you know, it would be enough, you know, that we could start over, over again.
\par EM:\tab Could you tell me if at that time the Germans would come into Jewish homes and rob their houses or...
\par DG:\tab Well, they did more than that, because very shortly after my father left, there was a raid on our street. Now we lived in the Korte Kiebit Straat. It was a...
\par EM:\tab Korte, what do you, how do you spell it or how could you...
\par DG:\tab Korte Kiebit Straat? It\rquote s...
\par EM:\tab Korte Kiebits-...
\par DG:\tab Korte, which is, it means \'93little bird\'94 I believe. It\rquote s a kiebit bird. Korte, or \'93short\'94 it\rquote s actually. K-O-R-T-E, and Kiebit, K-I-E-B-I-T...
\par EM:\tab OK
\par DG:\tab Straat is \'93street.\'94
\par EM:\tab Oh, is street.
\par DG:\tab It was actually row homes. They were all attached. You know, two stories high.
\par EM:\tab Right.
\par DG:\tab And what happened very shortly after that was in the middle of the night sudden--we heard commotion. We, our house was #34, which was not at the end of the street. It was like towards, somewhat in the middle of the street. So th
ey, the Germans had blocked off both ends of the street. And what we heard a commotion was the yelling and the screaming that was going on, you know, when they came and they just took people right out of their beds.
\par EM:\tab But you said it was a little mixed neighborhood.
\par DG:\tab Yes.
\par EM:\tab Did they take the Belgians too? Or just...
\par DG:\tab No.
\par EM:\tab The Jews?
\par DG:\tab No, they didn\rquote t, because that\rquote s when the true colors showed up.
\par EM:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par DG:\tab Several of the non-Jews showed the Germans where the Jews lived. And when the--where the non-Jews lived, and they helped them. With that, I don\rquote 
t know, my mother was, was a woman, you know, that had a good head and was also very heroic. She quickly took my sister and I and took us upstairs. We lived on the--it\rquote s like the steps g
oing up and we lived on the first floor. There was a second floor above us where, where there was a skylight, you know, that you could push up. She got a ladder and we climbed up onto the roof, you know, through the skylight. She got rid of, she knew, she
 pushed the ladder away. And we went and we hid. And the roof was slightly tilted, slightly tilted. And the front had a stone wall. And we hid...
\par EM:\tab Behind that...
\par DG:\tab Behind that wall, stone wall. It was very difficult of course because my sister was a little baby, you know, and you know, my mother was saying, \'93Shh, be quiet and don\rquote t make any noises or anything like that.\'94
 In the meanwhile we could see and we could hear all the yelling and screaming that was going on of all the people that were being drag
ged out of their houses. And we saw some of them being beaten up. And we could finally hear, you know, where they came to our house. Because they rang the bell and when nothing happened over there they bashed in the doors, you know, and they came running 
through the house. And they didn\rquote t see any, of course we weren\rquote 
t there. They did go upstairs but when the skylight opened up, you know, we were here. The pitch was this way. The skylight opened up this way. And they just looked around and they didn\rquote t see anything, fortunately for us.
\par EM:\tab So they didn\rquote t take the ladder to go up there or anything like that?
\par DG:\tab They did take the ladder...
\par EM:\tab They did take the ladder?
\par DG:\tab But they didn\rquote t go onto the roof. They just poked their heads through and shown their flashlights. But they didn\rquote t see us.
\par EM:\tab So that was at night you said.
\par DG:\tab At night, yeah.
\par EM:\tab At night, at night.
\par DG:\tab It was three, about 3:00 in the morning. So, they left. And as soon as my mother made sure, you know, that it was safe to get back into the
 house, you know, we went back inside. And it was an absolute mess. They ransacked the whole house. There was no furniture that was left, you know, that wasn\rquote 
t broken or anything like that. I mean it was a real mess. Because, we heard the whole commotion, you know, but we just didn\rquote t know what was happening. And we couldn\rquote 
t get out, because they had barricaded the door. You know, they had nailed the whole front shut.
\par EM:\tab Of the building.
\par DG:\tab Of the...
\par EM:\tab Of the apar-...
\par DG:\tab The door, the door of the house was nailed shut, because they had smashed the door in. And they nailed it shut. Now we lived behind the railroad tracks. Remember I mentioned to you it\rquote 
s a very, very--at that point we did not live too far from the train station. So at that point, you know, you have all the different tracks, you know, that are coming and so it\rquote s a very wide...
\par EM:\tab Area?
\par DG:\tab Area. And our house was behind the railroad tracks and we had the house and the little backyard where we had the outhouse, because we didn\rquote t have any indoor plumbing at that particular time, although we did have water. But we didn\rquote 
t have a bathroom. So we used to take, you know, in the olden days, my mother had this big, I don\rquote t know what you call it, the pan, a big pan or the vat, whatever it is, and she used to boil the water, you know, and...
\par EM:\tab And that\rquote s how...
\par DG:\tab We would sit in it, you know, and that\rquote s how we would get our baths. But anyway, when everything was quiet, you know, she told us not to make any sounds, you know, and not to do anything. 
And my mother left, at night. And my mother had already at that particular time...
\par EM:\tab What, did she get out through the window or...
\par DG:\tab She went out through the back yard.
\par EM:\tab Oh.
\par DG:\tab The back yard which was not, you know, the front was...
\par EM:\tab Was shut.
\par DG:\tab Shut, you know, but the back was not. And she was able, I don\rquote 
t know how in the world she managed to climb up, you know, onto the railroad tracks. But she did that and she was able to contact the underground. My mother had made, already had started, had enough sense to make contact with the Belgian underground.

\par EM:\tab Were these gentile Belgians, or were they Jews or mixed?
\par DG:\tab Some, some of them were Jewish.
\par EM:\tab Some of, oh.
\par DG:\tab Some of them were Jewish. That\rquote s how she made contact with them. And what she
 was able to do, was able to make arrangements to place my sister and I in a convent. That was the first place, while she, you know, the convent was away, you know, from Antwerp, and it would be a safe place. So that\rquote s where we went.
\par EM:\tab Who brought you to the convent? Did...
\par DG:\tab My mother did.
\par EM:\tab Yeah.
\par DG:\tab My mother did, and, and the, like I said the underground people helped her. Because they, they were the ones that brought the car.
\par EM:\tab You went by car?
\par DG:\tab We went by car. And all this was done at night.
\par EM:\tab Was that many days after that action that they had in--when they got all the people?
\par DG:\tab Yeah, it...
\par EM:\tab Was it several days later?
\par DG:\tab Several days later, yeah. Several days later.
\par EM:\tab But up to that time you stayed in the apartment?
\par DG:\tab In the house.
\par EM:\tab In the house.
\par DG:\tab Yeah. And we, we ate whatever food, you know, was left, you know, I mean that they didn\rquote t break or anything. Because they just left a mess. I\rquote m talking about, you know, everything was splattered on the floor, you know. Everything w
as broken.
\par EM:\tab Do you happen to know how many people were taken that day, approximately?
\par DG:\tab No.
\par EM:\tab Were there any Jews left in...
\par DG:\tab Yes. There...
\par EM:\tab Antwerp after that?
\par DG:\tab Yeah, yes, there were.
\par EM:\tab Oh.
\par DG:\tab But they were like, sudden raids. They--I think there were several of these raids, you know, that happened, one after another.
\par EM:\tab Do you know where these people were taken?
\par DG:\tab No, I don\rquote t know. I don\rquote t know.
\par EM:\tab But they were all taken families. I mean women and children.
\par DG:\tab It was everybody.
\par EM:\tab Everybody.
\par DG:\tab Everybody was taken out. Everybody was taken out. And what hurt, what hurt were these non-Jewish people that helped. Not, now I have to say this not everybody did. The people I was telling you abo
ut, the grocery store and all that, those people were wonderful people, and they did not help the Germans at all. They were decent people. But there were other people, there was one in particular I remember. And he was a policeman, that family that lived 
there. And they were going around, you know, showing the Germans, you know, where the Jews lived. So, we went to that convent and we didn\rquote t stay there very long. We only stayed there for a couple of months.
\par EM:\tab Did the people in the convent knew that you were Jewish, that these were Jewish children?
\par DG:\tab There were very few people that knew. It was the Mother Superior. The Mother Superior knew, and a few nuns knew.
\par EM:\tab Were there many children in that convent?
\par DG:\tab Yes, there were a lot of children.
\par EM:\tab Mostly, many Jewish children do you know?
\par DG:\tab No, there weren\rquote t...
\par EM:\tab Or you don\rquote t know?
\par DG:\tab Yes. There were some Jewish children, because what happened was in December suddenly my mother shows up and takes us out of there and as well and warned...
\par EM:\tab That was in, excuse me, that was in 1942, right?
\par DG:\tab December, 1942.
\par EM:\tab 1942. OK
\par DG:\tab December, 1942. My mother is, has been told by the underground that the Germans found out that there were Jews being hidden there and they were going to raid...
\par EM:\tab The convent.
\par DG:\tab The convent.
\par EM:\tab So she warned the Mother Superior. All the Jewish children were taken out of there. And so now my mother had the problem, you know, of being responsible for us again, you know, and then doing something. So she hid us, you know, with so
me Christian people that she knew. But we couldn\rquote t stay there for very long.
\par DG:\tab Tell me, these non-Jewish people that took you in, were they being paid or did they do it for nothing?
\par EM:\tab They did it for nothing. The people that my mother...
