\par }\pard \qj \fi540\li0\ri0\sl289\slmult0\nowidctlpar\tx0\tx720\tx1440\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\tx5040\tx5760\tx6480\tx7200\tx7920\tx8640\tx9360\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs24 
\par EM:\tab This is tape one, side two, interview with Mr. Daniel Goldsmith, Edith Millman interviewing.
\par DG:\tab So again I\rquote ll repeat. The people that my mother dealt with, they did it without any pay. They were humanitarian people.
\par EM:\tab Was there any punishment if they had been caught?
\par DG:\tab Absolutely. It would have been, it was death.
\par EM:\tab Was the dea-...
\par DG:\tab Death.
\par EM:\tab Did they threaten with death or...
\par DG:\tab Absolutely. Because they, part of the edicts, you know, which came out, you know, when the, 
all the restrictions were coming, after the raids, OK, the edict came out you know that, you know, you can not deal with a Jew. You can not hide a Jew, you know, on the punishment of death. So, through them, my mother decided, through them meaning the Bel
g
ian underground, my mother decided to split my sister and I up. And so what she wound up doing is placing my sister with a private Christian family. And myself, she wound up placing me in an orphanage. The orphanage was run by a Father Cornelius, who had 
several orphanages. He was a very good man, but he also was a Catholic man.
\par EM:\tab It wasn\rquote t a monastery or anything like that.
\par DG:\tab No.
\par EM:\tab It was an orphanage run...
\par DG:\tab It was an orphanage for boys. Orphanage for boys, where the first orphanage where they took me, you know, which was in Weelde, you know, was actually a very nice place because...
\par EM:\tab You, you\rquote re talking about the convent now? Where was the convent?
\par DG:\tab No.
\par EM:\tab Where is the...
\par DG:\tab I don\rquote t know where the convent was. That\rquote s one thing I don\rquote t know.
\par EM:\tab You don\rquote t remember.
\par DG:\tab I don\rquote t remember that. And neither did my mother. Otherwise I would have made a point...
\par EM:\tab Con-...
\par DG:\tab You know, to find out. But she just couldn\rquote t remember where it was.
\par EM:\tab Mmm hmm. So...
\par DG:\tab But...
\par EM:\tab So then you went to an orphanage. And...
\par DG:\tab And then I went to an orphanage, right. And this orphanage, like I said was in Weelde.
\par EM:\tab How do you spell that?
\par DG:\tab That\rquote s W-E-E-L-D-E.
\par EM:\tab OK. OK.
\par DG:\tab Weelde. And like I said, you know, it was run by Father Cornelius, oh, not Cornelius. Cornelissen, Cornelissen.
\par EM:\tab Cornelissen.
\par DG:\tab C-O-R-N-E-L-I-S-S-E-N. Cornelissen. And it was a very nice place. I\rquote m talking about the place, you know, where you learned farming, you know, where you were out in the open air, where you raise
d animals, particularly pigs. Things like that, you learned, you learned quite a bit over there. One thing I have to say is that he also was a Catholic priest, you know, and he tried very hard to convert me.
\par EM:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par DG:\tab But I would not convert. Because with--I always had with me a }{\i\fs24 siddur}{\fs24  [Hebrew prayer book]. This was the one thing that I always had with me, a }{\i\fs24 siddur}{\fs24 
. And he was not successful, you know, in converting me. However, he had to make sure, you know, that I was not conspicuous, you know, with the other children.
\par EM:\tab Right.
\par DG:\tab OK, because he was the only one that knew that I was Jewish. No one else knew.
\par EM:\tab Do you know if you were the only Jewish child? Or do you think there were...
\par DG:\tab In that orphanage, I think I was. There was a second orphanage which I know I wasn\rquote t. And I\rquote ll explain that to you later on. The--what he did, you know, is he made me go, you know, into Catholic school, like with the other children.

\par EM:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par DG:\tab And that kind of made things, you know, a lot easier. But he wasn\rquote t, he didn\rquote t want, you know, to leave things alone because he wasn\rquote 
t too sure, you know, if I would be found out or what, you know. So he moved me. After a while he moved me to the other orphanage, which was in Mechelen. That particular orphanage...
\par EM:\tab He was also in charge? I mean he...
\par DG:\tab Yeah, he was in charge.
\par EM:\tab He had connection with...
\par DG:\tab He had...
\par EM:\tab Both orphanages?
\par DG:\tab Yeah. That one, you know, however, I didn\rquote t know it at that particular time but I 
found out later on that there were more Jewish children there. And there, not only did I go to Catholic school, but I went to church. I became an altar boy. I learned everything about Catholicism. And, oh...
\par EM:\tab What was the name of that orphanage, do you remember? The second orphanage. Or do you know where it was?
\par DG:\tab In, I only know the name of the orphanage was in Mechelen.
\par EM:\tab In Mech-...
\par DG:\tab Mechelen. It\rquote s spelled M-E-C-H-E-L-E-N.
\par EM:\tab OK.
\par DG:\tab But I don\rquote t remember exactly the name of it per se.
\par EM:\tab OK, if it doesn\rquote t come...
\par DG:\tab But that was an orphanage in Mechelen where--and by the way, what he also did in order to make things a lot more, let\rquote s say right for the outside world, is he created false baptismal papers for me. This is, again, he was trying to
 get them legitimately by converting me. But since I didn\rquote 
t, you know, he finally did agree, you know, to make the false baptismal pa-, and also changed my name. And my name at that--when I was in the orphanage, was Willie Peters, which is a typical Belgian...
\par EM:\tab Willie.
\par DG:\tab Willie Peters, a typical Belgian name. In there, like I said, everything--I went to school--and everything, you know, seemed to be basically normal. Now we\rquote re talking already about, you know, going from, you know, in the first orphanag
e it was in 1943, OK? Now we\rquote re talking about the end of 1943 is when he put me in the other orphanage. And now we\rquote re talking about the beginning of 1944.
\par EM:\tab So that that time you were about 13 years old?
\par DG:\tab No, 12.
\par EM:\tab 12.
\par DG:\tab 12.
\par EM:\tab 12, OK.
\par DG:\tab 12 years old. Because I was born in December.
\par EM:\tab Oh, I see, OK.
\par DG:\tab OK, of the year, so I was 12 years old. And then everything was coming along okay until one day suddenly the Germans showed up, under the clear blue sky. And what they did is they gathered all 
the boys--it was a very simple thing for them to do--and they made everybody undress. And everybody that was Jewish was circumcised.
\par EM:\tab And the Belgian usually don\rquote t circumcise?
\par DG:\tab No.
\par EM:\tab They\rquote re not circumcised.
\par DG:\tab They\rquote re not circumcised. There was one other little boy that had a problem because he did have an operation on his penis, but it was not a circumcision. But they took him anyway, you know, because they weren\rquote 
t sure, you know. But, here we were, you know, all the Jewish kids, even though we didn\rquote t know by ourselves, you know, that we were Jewish, amongst ourselves. But the Jewish kids were circumcised. And nothing helped. The papers didn\rquote 
t help, you know, the name didn\rquote t help. All the witnesses didn\rquote t help. And nothing helped. So they took us to prison. And...
\par EM:\tab How many children were with you, do you remember?
\par DG:\tab Six.
\par EM:\tab Six boys.
\par DG:\tab Six boys. They took us to prison and over there, you know, they tried to, you know, to find out, you know, if we knew more, you know. There was questioning going on. By that time, by the way, it was May...
\par EM:\tab Of \lquote 44?
\par DG:\tab May of \lquote 44.
\par EM:\tab \lquote 44.
\par DG:\tab May \lquote 44. And none of us knew, you know. So they had no use for us anymore. And so what happened was, you know, they put us on a train. And they put--but, in the prison, you know, I met other children. I mean it wasn\rquote 
t just us, you know, there were other children that were there. They put us on a train. And we started going, we didn\rquote t know where we were going. But there was this one young 
boy, you know, who was older than we were, you know, who was a real fighter. And he says, \'93You know, we have to escape from the train.\'94 And that\rquote 
s what we did. We escaped from the train. Twenty, about twenty children, you know, were able to leave...
\par EM:\tab Was it a regular train or was it one of the cattle car trains?
\par DG:\tab Yeah, one of those cattle cars.
\par EM:\tab Cattle, a cattle car train.
\par DG:\tab And...
\par EM:\tab How did you escape? How did you do it?
\par DG:\tab He did it by, I don\rquote t know where he got hold from, we got a hold of a
 piece of iron. And he was able to, to--now, the other thing that I want to say, even though this was a train, you know, it was apparently, apparently it was not as well guarded as you would--some of the other trains were, because, I don\rquote 
t know for what reason. But whatever it was it wasn\rquote t as well guarded, so that he was able to take the metal piece that he had with him and break the piece of wood enough, you know, for us to slide through.
\par EM:\tab Well was the train moving or no?
\par DG:\tab Yeah. But what he did is he waited, you know, for when the train was slowing down at a curve.
\par EM:\tab Yeah.
\par DG:\tab And then it\rquote s when he said, \'93Go!\'94 So that\rquote s how we escaped. Now, once we all got back together again, because we all got, you know...
\par EM:\tab They jumped out at...
\par DG:\tab We jumped 
at different places. We all got back together again. And the first thing that we did is, again, two things. It happened at night, OK? And fortunately for us, we were near a group of trees. It was not a forest per se, you know, but certainly a group of tre
es, you know, where we were able, you know, to get in there and hide. But we didn\rquote t know where we were. We didn\rquote 
t know where we were. So we decided, you know, to hide during the day and at night, you know, to, like a couple of us, you know, older ones, you know, would go out and try to find out, you know, where we were. And try, we couldn\rquote 
t talk to anybody, but at least, you know, if you could see a sign, you know, or something like that.
\par EM:\tab Were you still in Belgium? In...
\par DG:\tab Yeah, we were still in Belgiu
m. And what we wound up doing, once we found out we were in Belgium, the oldest boy went to a church. I mean it was very, very risky, you know, but we felt, you know, we had no other choice. Went to a church, spoke to the father over there, and we hit it 
lucky. He took us in, and what he did is he placed every one of us with a Christian family, but nobody knew where anybody was. And the other Christian families didn\rquote 
t know that there were other children, you know, in town, being hidden. Nobody knew. Nobody 
knew, only the priest. And I was placed with this one family, Monsieur and Madame Botier. And what they did is they hid me in the attic. One of the good things about this, though, was that--I couldn\rquote t show my face, of course, you know, I couldn
\rquote t see or he
ar anything--was that they had a, again, this is one of these little villages, you know, where all the houses are attached. So you have long, deep gardens, you know, they had. So I was able to at least go out at night because there was no light. And I had
 
to do it very quietly. And I spent some time outside at night. But during the day I was up in the attic. People were very, very kind to me. They were older people. They had two daughters. At that particular time one was 18; I believe the other one was abo
ut 20. And they kept me there until we got liberated. Now remember, I\rquote m in Belgium, OK? So we got liberated in September, 1944. Remember, June is when the invasion started, you know...
\par EM:\tab [unclear].
\par DG:\tab And we got liberated in September, 1944. And I even have a couple of pictures I brought with me. They\rquote re not very good pictures but that was the liberation of the town. And, OK, let me regress a little bit, OK? My mother knew where I was.  

\par EM:\tab How...
\par DG:\tab 
But she also found out that, through the underground, of course. You know, she knew the priest, you know, and she knew through the underground, you know, where I was. But she also found out from the underground that I had been captured. So she started loo
king for me, because she didn\rquote t know where I was. And my mother was in a--looking for me through another priest, a wonderful, wonderful man by the name of Father Andr\'e9
. And this is in the city of Namur, which is also in Belgium. Just a side note: Father Andr\'e9
 was recognized as a Righteous Gentile. [pause; tape off then on] He was recognized as a Righteous Gentile and his picture is one of the pictures that are on the United States Holocaust Museum. And of course his picture, I have a picture of him, you know
, when he was much younger.
\par EM:\tab Right.
\par DG:\tab But now he\rquote s passed away since. But he\rquote s much older...
\par EM:\tab So, he must have been in touch with the underground...
\par DG:\tab Yes he was.
\par EM:\tab At the time.
\par DG:\tab And he saved a lot of Jewish people. He was a wonderful, wonderful person. Here\rquote s another person, you know, he didn\rquote 
t take any money. And he helped a lot of Jews after the war also. Anyway, my mother was looking for me. And she was in a city in Namur. And there was an air raid, an Allied air raid. And my mother got c
aught in that air raid. And she lost a leg in the air raid. As a matter of fact, she was the only person that survived in that building. But she almost died because she was bleeding, you know, and her leg had been severed from her. And they took her to th
e
 hospital. And so when--this happened just before the liberation. And after we got liberated, Monsieur and Madame Botier, you know, they got in touch, you know, with the underground and they were trying to locate my mother. And they finally found my mothe
r in the hospital. And I went to see her. And I almost didn\rquote 
t recognize her. She aged twenty years. I mean she was white as a sheet and her hair was gray. And of course she was in terrible shape, you know. But eventually, you know, everything worked out OK and she came out of it.
\par EM:\tab Tell me, all this time was she on false papers? Or how did she go about, you know, who was hiding her or [unclear]...
\par DG:\tab She was, all this time, I mean, she was actually working with the, with the Belgian underground. She had false papers also. She was caught--I can\rquote 
t believe this--four times, and escaped four times. She was just absolutely heroic. And all this, I have to tell you this, all this was because of the light at the end of the tunnel, which basically was the hope, you
 know, that my father would come back, you know. We would be able, you know, to start a family again and be a family again. Later on she told me if she had known my father had been killed she wouldn\rquote 
t have done all this. And I believe her. I believe her. So, she moved around. She was never in one place, you know, for very long. She moved around a lot.
\par EM:\tab Tell me, now, tell me about, well, first of all, what happened to you later?
\par DG:\tab Oh, after...
\par EM:\tab So you were liberated when, in \lquote 44?
\par DG:\tab In September, 1944. And then very shortly after that the--I forgot the, it\rquote 
s a French committee, you know, for, you know, that helps Jewish children--went ahead and started collecting Jewish children from the Christian homes, and to try to bring them back together again, 
to try to reunite them with a, you know, with whatever family there would be later on, OK, and also to try to start a new life. I mean, after all, all these children, you know, missed several years, you know, of their childhood. So we were first put in a 
place called }{\i\fs24 Hommes de la-bas}{\fs24 , which again was a }{\i\fs24 chateau}{\fs24 .
\par EM:\tab Was that in France or in...
\par DG:\tab No, no.
\par EM:\tab Belgium. In Belgium?
\par DG:\tab This is always in Belgium. }{\i\fs24 Hommes de la-bas}{\fs24  was in Belgium, which was a }{\i\fs24 chateau}{\fs24 . Actually it was a big }{\i\fs24 chateau}{\fs24 , because half of the }{\i\fs24 chateau}{\fs24 , I\rquote 
ll never forget this, was occupied by us, and the other half was occupied by American troops. And I remember very vividly Thanksgiving  1944, because we had never heard, you know, of Thanksgiving. It was the first time we saw white bread, 
you know, and how you celebrate and how the Americans were celebrating the...
\par EM:\tab Thanksgiving.
\par DG:\tab The Thanksgiving. And little by little, you know, we, they were bringing us together.
\par EM:\tab But at that time you knew that your mother was alive. You were in touch with your mother at that time?
\par DG:\tab Yes. At that time I knew my mother was alive and also that my mother couldn\rquote t take care of me, you know. But so...
\par EM:\tab Right.
\par DG:\tab You know, because she was in the hospital for a very, very long time, a very long time. It was not only, the reason she was in the hospital for a long time was not only because she had lost a tremendous amount of blood, and that\rquote 
s how close she was to death, but she had to regain her strength. And then she wound up having, literally having a peg leg, because she had a very, very short stump left, you know. She didn\rquote 
t have an awful lot of her leg left. She had a very short stump left and it would have been very difficult, you know, for her, you know, to learn how to walk, because of the shor
t stump. So they kept her in the hospital for a long time. Anyway, after they got us, you know, from the }{\i\fs24 Hommes de la-bas}{\fs24 
, we stayed there for a few months and they started bringing in other children. Now these were children now that were starting to come 
in, you know, from Holland, from Germany, from Czechoslovakia, from Hungary, from Yugoslavia. These children actually were, this is why, what I mean by displaced persons camp, OK? Because it was not the same thing as they had in Germany but this was stric
tly for children. But these children knew for a fact, you know, they had lost their families. There was no place for them else to go. So, once we were a fairly large group, then they transferred us to another place, which was this place }{\i\fs24 
Aische En Refail}{\fs24 , OK?
\par EM:\tab How do you spell that?
\par DG:\tab }{\i\fs24 Aische En Refail}{\fs24 , it\rquote s three words. It\rquote s }{\i\fs24 Aische}{\fs24 , A-I-S-C-H-E, }{\i\fs24 En}{\fs24 , E-N...
\par EM:\tab Yeah.
\par DG:\tab }{\i\fs24 Refail}{\fs24 , I believe it\rquote s R-E-F-A-I-L.
\par EM:\tab OK.
\par DG:\tab You know,}{\i\fs24  Aische En Refail}{\fs24 . And that was a house, a fairly decent large house in 
which they took all of us children, OK? This is the place actually, it was in the country, it was on top of a hill. It had a beautiful view of the surrounding, you know, countryside. And this is the place where we started to learn how to live again. It wa
s run, you know, by a doctor and his wife. And we started to learn...
\par EM:\tab Were they Belgian or French, do you know?
\par DG:\tab No, they were Belgian, Belgian Jews.
\par EM:\tab Belgian.
\par DG:\tab Belgian Jews. Where we learned the basics of life so to speak, again. They separated us in groups of, in different groups in different ages, you know. We started learning things again. At the same token, at the...
\par EM:\tab The same...
\par DG:\tab At the same time, I should say, the Palestinians, Jews, the }{\i\fs24 Haganah}{\fs24 , actually, sent people over to help us learn Hebrew, and to start learning, you know, what is called }{\i\fs24 Hachsharah}{\fs24 
, which means, you know, to learn, work, you know, in the fields, you know, and agriculture and things like that.
\par EM:\tab So were children being taken out from there through the }{\i\fs24 Aliyah Bet}{\fs24 , through the illegal }{\i\fs24 Aliyah}{\fs24  [immigration to Palestine], to go...
\par DG:\tab Some of them wound up in the illegal }{\i\fs24 Aliyah}{\fs24 , yeah, eventually. I didn\rquote t see anybody go, OK? But some of them did wind up, because most of these children wound up in Israel. You know, they did...
\par EM:\tab Right.
\par DG:\tab A lot of them wound up in Cyprus, until they finally got to Israel. How I know that is really because the correspondence I used to have with them, you know, after the war. Unfortunately a lot of the correspondence got lost, but I 
do have some pictures so I can show you that. We had the pleasure of seeing the Jewish Brigade. I don\rquote t know whether you\rquote 
re aware but the Jewish Brigade, you know, was the Palestinian, you know, Jewish soldiers, you know, that fought with the British?
\par EM:\tab Right, right.
\par DG:\tab And they came to see us and we went to see them. And so we started living again. I\rquote m talking about we started keeping }{\i\fs24 Shabbas}{\fs24  again, you know. We started }{\i\fs24 davening}{\fs24 
 [saying prayers]. We started learning. We started going places. We started life again, except it was just amongst us none of us had any parents, you know, to go to. We didn\rquote 
t know, you know, what was happening, whether we were going to have any parents. Because believe it or not, for us this was the most difficult part of the war
, because now, you live for hope, OK. And now, the end has come. The war end has come, and now you\rquote 
re trying to hope, you know, and making sure, you know, that so-and-so is coming back and so-and-so is coming back. Those were very, very, very difficult tim
es. Most of us never saw our parents again, most of us. In my case, of course, I saw my mother, you know, but my father, you know, didn\rquote t come back.
\par EM:\tab Now tell me about your sister. What happened with your sister?
\par DG:\tab Oh. My sister was with a Christian family, which was very, very good to her. They really raised her. But there is a sad part to this story, and that is it\rquote 
s, it happened many times over and over again. When you give a family a baby, like remember my sister was a year-and-a-half, almost two y
ears old, and she spends two, two-and-a-half years with them, they become very, very attached to her, which is very, very understandable.
\par EM:\tab Right.
\par DG:\tab And so, it was 1945. So you\rquote re talking about my sister basically spent three years with them. In 1945, 
before my mother finally had enough energy and strength, you know, to come out of the hospital, at that point she is looking to claim her child. The problem is, you know, these people didn\rquote t want to give her up. It\rquote s a tragedy. It\rquote 
s a tragedy, I mean, you know, for the people who actually, you know, treated her very, very nicely. They, she became part of their family. But it\rquote s also my mother\rquote 
s child and she wants her back. So, it became a battle. Fortunately, unknown to us, my father\rquote s younger brother, the 
one that I had talked to you about that was the last one to leave home, came to Belgium as an American soldier, and started looking for us. And he found us. He found us just about the time, you know, when my mother was having a hard time, you know, with t
hese people. And so this is my uncle Moishe. And he used his influence as an American and as a, with American authority, you know? And he took my sister away from them. So here is...
\par EM:\tab Did your sister have a rough time adjusting to your mother?
\par DG:\tab She, it\rquote 
s, it's yes and no. Yes, because my mother in essence was a stranger to her, you know, at that particular time. But no, because when they took my sister away from them, you know, they put my sister with me. And that was with--in the home that I was in, O
K.
\par EM:\tab Oh, OK
\par DG:\tab Which is the home that I was telling you about in Porfancar, in }{\i\fs24 Aische En Refail}{\fs24 . And there she was with other children, you know. And myself, you know, being able, you know, to tell her, you know, who she is, etc., etc., it ma
de things a lot easier.
\par EM:\tab Mmm hmm.
\par DG:\tab OK? And after my mother got out of the hospital, she still couldn\rquote t take care of us, because she couldn\rquote t work. She was in the process, actually, with the help of Father Andr\'e9, in trying to get an artificial leg. So
 she had a hard time with that. So they transferred us from, now from this home to another home which was the }{\i\fs24 Hachsharah}{\fs24 
 of Marquin. It was like a school, again, a very, very large place. This was more religious. It was more Orthodox. And the same thing, it belonged to }{\i\fs24 B\rquote nai Akiva}{\fs24 
. But the point was, you know, to teach us a trade, to teach us how to take care of the land, you know, to prepare us, you know, to go to Palestine.
